(function(){var b="d34f3e4f88d8",m="Both are used to represent interrelated things of interest (entities) in a specific domain of knowledge\n- <strong>Entity-Relationship Model (ERM)</strong> - was introduced by Peter Chen in 1976 (see [first](http://bit.csc.lsu.edu/~chen/pdf/erd-5-pages.pdf) and [second](http://bit.csc.lsu.edu/~chen/pdf/Chen_Pioneers.pdf) articles)\n- <strong>Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD)</strong> - is a type of [[Model vs Diagram|diagram]] used to represent ERM (e.g. [[Data Models (Conceptual - Logical - Physical) Data Models|Data Models]])\n\n# ERD Notation Techniques\n\n```merge-table\n{\n  \"rows\": [\n    [\n      \"- [[ERD Crow's Foot Notation|Crow's Foot Notation]]\\n- [Chen Notation](https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chen-Notation)\\n- [IDEF1X Notation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IDEF1X)\\n- [Bechman Notation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_structure_diagram#Bachman_diagram)\\n- [Martin Notation](https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin-Notation)\\n- [Min/Max Notation](https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Min-Max-Notation) of Jean-Raymond Abrial in 1974\\n- <strong>[[Unified Modeling Language (UML) Diagram|UML]] Class Diagrams</strong>\",\n      \"![[Entity-Relationship Model (ERM) - Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD)/er-notation-techniques-comparison.png|301]]\"\n    ]\n  ]\n}\n```";if(window.__kgBody){window.__kgBody(b,m);}else{(window.__kgBodyQ=window.__kgBodyQ||[]).push([b,m]);}})();
